# Gridyard

A business workspace engine: a Rust/WASM spreadsheet-grade grid and
formula core, driven by declarative workspace definitions. Full vision
and architecture: `docs/00-index-and-vision.md`. The complete spec set
is `docs/00` through `docs/07` — read the relevant spec before
generating code for a given area, don't guess at behavior that's
already been decided there.

## Module boundaries

- `crates/` — the Rust/WASM engine. Only `gridyard-wasm` may depend on
  `wasm-bindgen`/`web-sys`. Every other crate (`gridyard-core`,
  `gridyard-formula`, `gridyard-graph`, `gridyard-grid`, `gridyard-io`)
  must stay plain, natively testable Rust with zero WASM dependency —
  this is deliberate, see `docs/07-repo-scaffolding-spec.md`.
- `packages/` — the TypeScript layer (`@gridyard/grid-renderer`,
  `@gridyard/workspace-runtime`, `@gridyard/ui-kit`). No Rust, no
  business logic that belongs in the engine — these consume the WASM
  boundary, they don't duplicate what it does.
- `apps/web-demo` — wires the packages together into a real app.
- `apps/mock-server` — serves mock JSON fixtures for the workspace
  runtime's REST adapter before a real backend exists.
- `docs/` — the spec set. Treat it as the source of truth; if
  implementation needs to diverge from a spec, update the spec in the
  same change, don't let them drift apart silently.

## Scope discipline

Don't build ahead of the current milestone in
`docs/06-mvp-scope-and-roadmap.md`. If a spec describes a later-phase
capability (AI/agent features, 400+ formula functions, full
collaboration), it's there for context, not a request to implement it
now.

